      "\n  have h1 : ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n    -- Use the fact that the integral over the product measure can be reduced to the integral over the relevant component.\n    -- This is a special case of Fubini's theorem, where we fix all other variables and integrate over one component.\n    calc\n      ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ := rfl\n      _ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n        -- Apply Fubini's theorem to fix all variables except the i-th one.\n        -- Since the measure is a product measure, we can integrate over the i-th component first.\n        have h2 : ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n          -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n          calc\n            ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ := rfl\n            _ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n              -- Use the fact that the integral over the product measure can be reduced to the integral over the relevant component.\n              -- This is a special case of Fubini's theorem, where we fix all other variables and integrate over one component.\n              have h3 : ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n                -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n                classical\n                -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n                calc\n                  ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ = ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) ∂Measure.pi μ := rfl\n                  _ = ∫ x : ℝ, f x ∂μ i := by\n                    -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n                    rw [← MeasureTheory.integral_fst]\n                    <;>\n                    simp [MeasureTheory.integral_comp]\n                    <;>\n                    congr 1 <;>\n                    ext1 x <;>\n                    simp [Function.comp]\n                    <;>\n                    rfl\n              -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n              exact h3\n        -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n        exact h2\n  -- Use the general version of Fubini's theorem to split the integral.\n  exact h1",
      "\n   To formalize this, perhaps we can find a theorem in Lean's library that says: if `F : X × Y → ℝ` is `F(x, y) = f(x)`, then `∫_{X × Y} F d(μ × ν) = ∫_X f dμ` when `ν` is a probability measure. \n\n   Looking at the library, we find `MeasureTheory.integral_prod_one`: if `μ` is a finite measure, and `ν` is a probability measure, then `∫ (x : X) (y : Y), f x ∂μ × ν = ∫ x, f x ∂μ`.\n\n   But our case is not a product of two spaces. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we can use that the product of probability measures is a probability measure and proceed inductively, but perhaps there is no need to.\n\n   Instead, perhaps we can use the fact that `Measure.pi` is defined as iterated products. \n\n   In Lean, we can find that `Measure.pi` is constructed recursively, and perhaps use induction. \n\n   But perhaps instead, we can use `Function.update` and express any function as a product.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we can factor `(Fin d → ℝ)` as `ℝ × (Fin (d-1) → ℝ)` by separating the coordinate `i`. \n\n   Here's a better approach:\n\n   Define `pr_i : (Fin d → ℝ) → ℝ` by `pr_i(a) = a i`.  \n\n   Then, `∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (a i) dμ = ∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (pr_i a) dμ`.\n\n   But since `μ` is the product of `μ_j` and each `μ_j` is a probability measure, then `pr_i` is measurable and its distribution is `μ_i`, i.e., `μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹ = μ_i`.\n\n   Therefore, `∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (pr_i a) dμ = ∫ x, f x d(μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹) x = ∫ x, f x dμ_i x`.\n\n   In Lean, this would correspond to using the change of variables formula: `∫ (a : Fin d → ℝ), f (pr_i a) dμ = ∫ x, f x d(μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹)`.\n\n   Then, we need to check that `μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹ = μ_i`.\n\n   So perhaps we can use `MeasureTheory.integral_comp` and show that `μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹ = μ_i`.\n\n   To do that, we can show that for any measurable set `A : measurableSet ℝ`, `(μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹) A = μ_i A`.\n\n   But `(μ ∘ pr_i⁻¹) A = μ {a : Fin d → ℝ | a i ∈ A} = ∏_{j} μ_j (if j = i then A else univ) = μ_i A * ∏_{j ≠ i} μ_j (univ) = μ_i A * 1 = μ_i A`.\n\n 